article.description: Michael Finley had 19 points and Dirk Nowitzki recovered from a two-point first half to finish with 18 as the Mavericks overcame their sluggish start and improved on the league's best record by beating the Nuggets 86-71 Monday night.
article.headline: Mavericks win ugly against lowly Nuggets
article.linkText: LaFrentz gets it going as Mavs defeat Nuggets
article.story:
DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas Mavericks took a while to get going against the team with the worst record in the Western Conference.
Finley

Michael Finley had 19 points and Dirk Nowitzki recovered from a two-point first half to finish with 18 as the Mavericks overcame their sluggish start and improved on the league's best record by beating the Nuggets 86-71 Monday night. "Good teams have to win ugly games and that's what it's all about,'' Nowitzki said. Reserve Raef LaFrentz had 16 points and 11 rebounds, both season highs, to help Dallas improve to 17-2 at home and 28-5 overall. Ex-Maverick Juwan Howard's 22 points and 14 rebounds paced the Nuggets, who have lost 12 of 13 overall and seven in a row to Dallas. Denver, which has scored 100 points only once this season, set a season-low for points by a Dallas opponent. The Nuggets committed 24 turnovers, the most by a Dallas foe this season, and the Mavericks capitalized on a season-high 27 points off those turnovers. "Give them a lot of credit,'' Denver coach Jeff Bzdelik said. "They can change up defenses and against young guards, it can frustrate them. We missed a lot of shots, which is our Achilles' heel. We yield 27 points off 24 turnovers and you can't do that. They have too many guns.'' On Saturday, the Mavericks routed the Philadelphia 76ers 102-83 in a nationally televised game. But the Mavs were unable to summon the same kind of effort against the Nuggets, who fell to 7-26. "We came out and got lulled into a slow game and as a result we were sluggish,'' Finley said. "We then started to pick it up defensively and as a result we picked up the tempo.'' Dallas won despite shooting 41 percent from the field and missing 12-of-15 from 3-point range. Nowitzki went 1-for-6 from the field in the first half, then scored six points during a 10-2 third-quarter run as the Mavericks pushed the pace and went ahead 59-52. "We wanted to speed it up a little in the third quarter and get our style of play,'' Finley said. Dallas held a 64-59 advantage after three quarters, and began the fourth with a 9-2 run capped by LaFrentz's tip-in with 9:17 to play for a 73-61 edge. Nowitzki's three-point play with 5:58 remaining gave Dallas an 82-64 lead, and Denver was never able to pull closer than 13 points the rest of the way. The Mavericks trailed throughout the first half, allowing the Nuggets to slow the tempo. Dallas rallied to tie the score at 40 on LaFrentz's corner jumper with 3.8 seconds left in the second quarter. LaFrentz had been struggling since his return from missing 13 games due to a sprained ankle. Coach Don Nelson had been critical of LaFrentz's effort. "I thought that Raef took a major step toward being the player that we hope that he is,'' Nelson said. "We needed him tonight. There was no question that we needed something from somebody.'' LaFrentz said hitting some early shots boosted his confidence. "I've been working hard the last week and tonight I felt pretty good,'' LaFrentz said. "Some shots fell and it turned into a pretty decent night.'' Denver was in front after the first quarter 20-14 behind Howard's 12 points as Dallas had its lowest-scoring quarter of the season. The Mavericks hit only 6-of-18 field goal attempts in the first quarter, 14-of-37 in the first half. Dallas missed all six first-half 3-point attempts and was outrebounded in the opening half 26-17. "It's like pulling teeth against the Denver Nuggets,'' Nelson said. "They control the tempo. When you get into a game where you don't shoot very well, they have a chance to win.''

Game notes
Denver requested waivers on guard John Crotty, who's been out with a strained right Achilles' tendon. He signed with the Nuggets on Dec. 22 and has appeared in only four games. ... Dallas guard Walt Williams returned to the rotation after missing four games with a strained left knee. ... The Mavericks have won 22 of the last 27 meetings with the Nuggets, 10 straight in Dallas.
